---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout>
  <main class="min-h-screen bg-slate-950 text-slate-100">
    <section class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 py-20 sm:py-28">
      <p
        class="mb-4 inline-flex rounded-full border border-slate-700 bg-slate-900/70 px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium tracking-wide text-slate-300"
      >
        Stove Philosophy
      </p>
      <h1
        class="max-w-3xl text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-white sm:text-6xl"
      >
        the ancient art of enduring heat, waiting patiently, and accepting that
        some things just need to simmer.
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-6 max-w-3xl text-base leading-7 text-slate-300 sm:text-lg">
        Core Principles:
      </p>
      <div class="mt-10 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <a
          href="#latest"
          class="rounded-md bg-white px-5 py-2.5 text-sm font-semibold text-slate-900 transition hover:bg-slate-200"
        >
          Read the principles
        </a>
        <a
          href="#about"
          class="rounded-md border border-slate-600 px-5 py-2.5 text-sm font-semibold text-slate-100 transition hover:bg-slate-800"
        >
          Meditation on the flame
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section
      id="latest"
      class="mx-auto grid max-w-5xl gap-5 px-6 pb-16 sm:grid-cols-2"
    >
      <article class="rounded-xl border border-slate-800 bg-slate-900/60 p-5">
        <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-slate-400">
          Core Principle I
        </p>
        <h2 class="mt-2 text-lg font-semibold text-white">Embrace the Flame</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-slate-300">
          You cannot control the burner of fate, only how you respond to it.
          When life turns up the heat, do not flee the kitchen. Stand firm,
          adjust your temperature settings, and remember: even the greatest
          meals require discomfort.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="rounded-xl border border-slate-800 bg-slate-900/60 p-5">
        <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-slate-400">
          Core Principle II
        </p>
        <h2 class="mt-2 text-lg font-semibold text-white">
          The Virtue of Preheating
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-slate-300">
          Preparation is everything. The hasty chef who throws ingredients into
          a cold pan achieves only disappointment. So too must you preheat your
          mind before facing the day's challenges. Rushing leads to sticking.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="rounded-xl border border-slate-800 bg-slate-900/60 p-5">
        <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-slate-400">
          Core Principle III
        </p>
        <h2 class="mt-2 text-lg font-semibold text-white">
          All Things in Their Season(ing)
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-slate-300">
          Add salt at the right moment, not before, not after. Timing matters.
          Patience is not weakness—it is knowing when something needs five more
          minutes, even when you're hungry now.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="rounded-xl border border-slate-800 bg-slate-900/60 p-5">
        <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-slate-400">
          Core Principle IV
        </p>
        <h2 class="mt-2 text-lg font-semibold text-white">
          Accept What Cannot Be Unburnt
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-slate-300">
          The toast is blackened. The soup has boiled over. Lamenting changes
          nothing. Scrape what can be salvaged, learn, and move forward.
          Dwelling on culinary disaster only ensures the next course also burns.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="rounded-xl border border-slate-800 bg-slate-900/60 p-5">
        <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-slate-400">
          Core Principle V
        </p>
        <h2 class="mt-2 text-lg font-semibold text-white">
          The Four Burners of Life
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-slate-300">
          Family, work, health, friends. The ancient Stoves teach that you
          cannot keep all four on high simultaneously. Accept this. Something
          must be set to simmer, or you'll scorch everything.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="rounded-xl border border-slate-800 bg-slate-900/60 p-5">
        <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-slate-400">
          Core Principle VI
        </p>
        <h2 class="mt-2 text-lg font-semibold text-white">
          Memento Mori...tality of Leftovers
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-slate-300">
          Remember: all food expires. Even that which seems preserved will
          eventually spoil. This is not cause for despair, but urgency—eat the
          good cheese today, for tomorrow it may be fuzzy.
        </p>
      </article>
    </section>

    <section id="about" class="border-y border-slate-800 bg-slate-900/40">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 py-14">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white">Stove Philosophy</h2>
        <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-sm leading-7 text-slate-300 sm:text-base">
          Endure the heat. Respect preparation. Honor timing. Accept mistakes.
          Balance the burners. Remember the leftovers. This is the practice.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <footer class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 py-10 text-xs text-slate-400">
      © {new Date().getFullYear()} Stove Philosophy.
    </footer>
  </main>
</Layout>
